# SEAL Team 6 for One Farmer. Rented Buses for 5,000 Students.

## What Nigeria Refuses to Learn About Protecting Its Citizens

---

### 1985 — Mexico

A DEA agent named Kiki Camarena is kidnapped, tortured for 30 hours, and murdered by the Guadalajara Cartel.

America's response? President Reagan ordered every vehicle crossing the US-Mexico border searched, effectively paralysing commerce between the two nations. The DEA launched Operation Leyenda, its largest homicide investigation ever. The entire Guadalajara Cartel was dismantled. Every leader was hunted, arrested, or killed. Forty years later, in 2025, the man who ordered the killing was extradited to a Brooklyn courtroom and now faces the death penalty.

**The result?** No cartel has deliberately killed a DEA agent since. Because they learned that killing an American agent is bad for business.

One agent. One nation's full wrath. Forty years of pursuit.

---

### 2020 — Nigeria

Philip Walton, a 27-year-old American farmer, was kidnapped from his home near the Niger-Nigeria border by six armed men.

America's response? Within 96 hours, Navy SEAL Team 6 was deployed. They tracked the kidnappers' phones, flew into Northern Nigeria under cover of darkness, and extracted Walton alive. Several captors were killed. No American was injured.

Secretary of State Pompeo said: *"We will never abandon any American taken hostage."*

96 hours. SEAL Team 6. Into another sovereign nation. For one citizen.

---

### 2023 — Sudan

Civil war erupts. Foreign nationals are trapped in Khartoum.

America sent approximately 100 special operations troops in three MH-47 helicopters, sweeping in and out of the capital with helicopters on the ground for less than an hour. No shots fired. Embassy staff were airlifted to safety. Then armed drones escorted a convoy of buses carrying hundreds of Americans on a 500-mile journey to Port Sudan.

India launched Operation Kaveri, deploying IAF C-130J aircraft with armed Garud commandos who kept engines running on the tarmac while they secured and evacuated nearly 3,862 citizens.

Germany launched Operation Raus aus Khartum, flying eight military flights and evacuating 740 people in just two days.

Most countries deployed military transport aircraft to fly their people out.

**Nigeria?** The evacuation began slowly, with only 15 of the 40 buses required being provided. Nigerians were stranded in the desert after buses ran out of fuel. There were delays caused by the Central Bank of Nigeria and requests for visa payments by the Egyptian government. Thousands of stranded Nigerians, many of them students, endured difficult journeys through conflict zones to reach designated evacuation points.

No military aircraft. No armed escort. No commandos. Rented buses. Payment delays. Students walking through a war zone.

---

### And Then... Home.

In November 2025, 25 schoolgirls were kidnapped from a boarding school in Kebbi state. Three days later, 303 students and 12 teachers were kidnapped from a Catholic school in Niger state.

More than 1,680 students have been abducted across Nigeria since the Chibok kidnapping in 2014.

Between July 2024 and June 2025 alone, 4,722 people were kidnapped across Nigeria, with at least 762 killed. Nigerians paid a staggering ₦2.23 trillion in ransom to kidnappers between May 2023 and April 2024.

The list reads like a recurring nightmare: 344 boys in Katsina (2020). 279 girls in Zamfara (2021). 136 students in Niger state (2021). 150 in Kaduna (2021). Over 200 in Kaduna (2024). 303 in Niger state (2025).

Hundreds of children. Dragged into the bush. Again. And again. And again.

---

### Now Sit With This.

America sent SEAL Team 6 across international borders for **one** farmer.

America shut down an entire international border and hunted a cartel for **forty years** for **one** agent.

India flew armed commandos into a warzone for its students.

Germany moved 740 people in **two days**.

Nigeria has watched **thousands** of its children dragged from classrooms into forests, year after year, and the pattern repeats.

Inaction is a message. Silence is a message. And the message Nigerians are receiving from their own government is clear:

*You are on your own.*

When a government protects its people with everything it has, it doesn't just save lives. It builds something you cannot buy: **patriotism**. Citizens who know their nation will come for them will fight for that nation, build for that nation, bleed for that nation.

When a government abandons its people, it kills something no policy can resurrect: **belief**.

Nigerians, you deserve a government that makes the world understand one thing:

**You do not touch our people.**

Not one. Not ever.

